                    <person name="Ancus Marcius"/>
                    <emphasis method="pen" type="curved" text="Historia"/>
                </position>
            </language>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>5. Tarquinij Prisci historia regia.</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Tarquin the Elder"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>5. Royal history of Tarquinus Priscus.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>} nota distinctionem Regni, et Reipub[licae].</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Note the difference between the kingdom and the republic.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Qui philosophi enituerint regnante apud Romanos Tarquinio Prisco; apud Hebraeos Sedechia; cum Hierusalem capta est, 
                        templumque subversu[m]. August. l. 18. c. 25. de civit. Dei. Ex Eusebio. nempe septem Sapientes. (qui tamen s[upr]a regnante Romulo).
                        Item Anaximander, et Anaximenes, et Xenophanes physici. Tunc et Pythagoras, ex quo coeperunt appellari philosophi. 
                        Consulendae chronologiae. Certe temporibus regum Cyri, Croesi, Pisistrati, floruerunt septem sapientes. 
                        Cyro autem rege, populus Judaeus est solutus.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Tarquin the Elder"/>
                    <person name="Zedekiah"/>
                    <person name="Augustine"/>
                    <person name="Eusebius"/>
                    <person name="Romulus"/>
                    <person name="Anaximander"/>
                    <person name="Anaximenes"/>
                    <person name="Xenophanes"/>
                    <person name="Pythagoras"/>
                    <person name="Cyrus the Great"/>
                    <person name="Pisistratus"/>
                    <book title="De Civitate Dei"/>
                    <location name="Jerusalem"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>What philosophers achieved distinction during the reign of Tarquinius Priscus over the Romans and Zedekiah over the Hebrews, 
                at the time when Jerusalem was captured and the temple overthrown: Augustine, City of God, bk. 18, c. 25, based on Eusebius. 
                This concerns the seven sages, of course, (about whom see above, during the reign of Romulus), and also the natural scientists Anaximander, 
                Anaximenes and Xenophanes. During that period also Pythagoras lived, from whose time such men began to be called philosophers. 
                One should consider the chronology. Certainly the seven sages thrived in the period of the kings Cyrus, Croesus, Pisistratus. 
                And in fact while Cyrus was king the Jewish people were released.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
